  "hash": "sha256:a3f7c2e14b09d856f3a1cc7e2d94b0f1e85a3c7d2b6e9f0a1c4d8e2f5b7a9c3d",
  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-class3",
      "rationale": "At MRL 5 for a Class III device, software quality assurance requires documented version control, regression testing, and formal release procedures. The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is managed under Git version control with tagged releases; regression test suite covers 47 canonical cases with automated pass/fail reporting. Release notes document all code changes between versions used in this assessment. Gradation 3 is achieved and meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/ncv-mrl5-class3",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for the Navier-Stokes solver and the power-law hemolysis transport equation. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical expectations (second-order spatial, first-order temporal). Three benchmark cases from the FDA Critical Path initiative were reproduced within published tolerances. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/disc-error-mrl5-class3",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh refinement study was conducted across three grid levels (coarse 2.1M, medium 5.8M, fine 14.2M cells) following the GCI method of Celik et al. (2008). Grid convergence index values for hemolysis index were below 3.2% on the fine grid. Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the continuum limit; the fine-grid solution lies within 1.8% of the extrapolated value. Gradation 4 is achieved, satisfying the MRL 5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions for the FDA generic centrifugal pump were reproduced from the published protocol: bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 35±2%, five operating points (3500–5000 RPM, 2–8 L/min). Temperature, viscosity, and inlet boundary conditions in the CFD model were matched to within measurement uncertainty of the experimental setup. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against experimental measurements at all five operating points. Mean absolute error was 8.3% across operating conditions; maximum error was 14.1% at the highest flow-speed combination. Prediction intervals from Monte Carlo UQ encompassed all experimental measurements. Quantitative agreement metrics (MAPE, RMSE, 95% coverage) were computed and documented in the validation report. Gradation 4 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) — is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of chronic hemolysis. The hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen et al.) maps shear stress and exposure time to red blood cell damage, which is the mechanistic basis for the clinical threshold. QoI relevance is confirmed by regulatory precedent (FDA guidance on blood-contacting device testing) and the direct traceability from NIH to clinical hemolysis thresholds. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The validation activities for this factor were designed to mirror the clinical context of use as closely as practicable given the constraints of in-vitro hemolysis testing. The FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry was selected as the validation platform because it shares the impeller-volute topology, rotational speed range (3500–5000 RPM), and operating flow regime (2–8 L/min) with the target Class III VAD. Fluid properties — bovine blood at physiological hematocrit and temperature — are accepted surrogates for human blood in hemolysis assessments per ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance. Boundary conditions (inlet velocity profiles, outlet pressure waveforms) were derived from patient hemodynamic data representative of the VAD implant population, ensuring that the Reynolds and Stokes numbers at the impeller inlet fall within ±12% of the clinical operating envelope. The hemolysis power-law coefficients were calibrated on the same experimental dataset used for validation, with a held-out test partition to guard against overfitting; cross-validation confirmed coefficient stability across blood batches. Turbulence model selection (SST k-ω) was validated against particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements in the volute region, where the highest shear-stress gradients and the dominant contribution to hemolysis index accumulate. In summary, the geometry, fluid, boundary, and turbulence-model choices collectively ensure that the validation scenario is a high-fidelity analogue of the COU, and the achieved Gradation 4 reflects this comprehensive alignment. The assessment team is satisfied that no systematic gap exists between the validation platform and the intended clinical use that would materially affect the predicted NIH values or their uncertainty bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence was monitored via residual norms (continuity, momentum, hemolysis scalar) with convergence declared at 10^-5 for all equations. Round-off error was assessed by comparing double- and single-precision solutions; differences were below 0.1% for all QoIs. Solver settings are documented in the simulation log files archived with the validation report. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-mrl5",
      "rationale": "A simulation execution checklist was developed and followed for all production runs. An independent analyst repeated two of the five operating-point simulations from the archived input files and obtained results within 0.5% of the primary analyst results, confirming reproducibility. User-introduced variability is documented and bounded. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on its documented performance in rotating machinery hemolysis simulations. Model form uncertainty was estimated by comparing predictions from SST k-ω, realizable k-ε, and the Spalart-Allmaras model; spread across models was 11% in NIH. The power-law hemolysis model introduces additional form uncertainty estimated at ±18% based on published coefficient variability. Achieved Gradation 3 does not meet the required Gradation 4; this gap is acknowledged and contributes to the conservative uncertainty bounds applied in the decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification was performed on 12 model input parameters including blood viscosity, hematocrit, power-law exponents, inlet velocity profile shape, and rotational speed tolerance. Parameter distributions were derived from published measurement uncertainty data and device specifications. 10,000 Monte Carlo samples were propagated through the CFD surrogate (Kriging metamodel trained on 150 full CFD evaluations). 95th-percentile NIH predictions remained below the clinical threshold at all operating points. Gradation 4 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis measurements were obtained from three independent blood batches, each tested in duplicate at each operating point (n=6 per operating point). Inter-batch variability was characterized and incorporated into the experimental uncertainty bounds used for output comparison. Sample size is consistent with published practice for FDA pump validation studies. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equiv-inputs-mrl5",
      "rationale": "Input parameters used in the validation simulations (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions) were verified to be equivalent to those used in the COU simulations within stated tolerances. A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each validation input to its COU counterpart with documented justification for any differences. No material differences were identified that would invalidate the use of validation evidence for COU credibility assessment. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    }
  ],
